in the same way. —- 7. pratis: in- cluding the hay crop. The com- plaint that prata were displacing segetes was not new in the time of Varro (R. R. 2, prooem. 4). — 7. arbustis: most important among these would be the olive-yards (oli- veta), for the olive was one of the chief products of Italy, and its cul- tivation described in great detail by Cato. For orchards‚ cf. pomariis (l. 8). Vines trained upon trees (arbusta) call for no separate men- tion after vinea. —- 7. laetae: cf. on 53, 7.—8. pecudum pastu: here put in a lower rank than segetes, vineae, and the rest. In reality many great landlords gave up vast estates to their flocks and herds; cf.
